ðŸš€ 1. Setup & Import
code
Python
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

# Set options to see more rows/columns
pd.set_option('display.max_columns', None)
ðŸ“‚ 2. Loading & Saving Data
Format	Read Command	Write Command
CSV	pd.read_csv('file.csv')	df.to_csv('new.csv', index=False)
Excel	pd.read_excel('file.xlsx')	df.to_excel('new.xlsx')
SQL	pd.read_sql(query, connection)	df.to_sql('table', connection)
JSON	pd.read_json('file.json')	df.to_json('new.json')
ðŸ” 3. Inspecting Data
code
Python
df.head(5)       # View first 5 rows
df.tail(5)       # View last 5 rows
df.info()        # Data types, memory, and null counts
df.describe()    # Summary stats (mean, std, min, max)
df.shape         # Number of (rows, columns)
df.columns       # List of all column names
df['column'].value_counts() # Count of unique values
âœ‚ï¸ 4. Selection & Filtering
df['col_name']: Select one column (Series).
df[['col1', 'col2']]: Select multiple columns.
df.iloc[0:5, 0:3]: Select by index position (rows 0-4, cols 0-2).
df.loc[df['age'] > 21]: Filter rows based on a condition.
df.query('age > 21'): Clean way to filter using a string.
ðŸ§¹ 5. Data Cleaning (The "Janitor" Work)
Command	Action
df.dropna()	Remove all rows with missing values
df.fillna(0)	Replace missing values with 0 (or a mean)
df.drop_duplicates()	Remove identical rows
df.rename(columns={'old':'new'})	Rename columns
df.drop(['col1'], axis=1)	Delete a column
df['col'] = df['col'].astype(int)	Change data type
ðŸ”„ 6. Manipulation & Transformation
code
Python
# Create a new column
df['total'] = df['price'] * df['quantity']

# Sort data
df.sort_values(by='total', ascending=False)

# Apply a function to every row
df['name_upper'] = df['name'].apply(lambda x: x.upper())

# Map values
df['gender'] = df['gender'].map({'M': 1, 'F': 0})
ðŸ“Š 7. Grouping & Aggregation
code
Python
# Group by a column and calculate the mean of others
df.groupby('department')['salary'].mean()

# Multiple aggregations
df.groupby('city').agg({'age': 'mean', 'salary': 'sum'})
ðŸ”— 8. Combining DataFrames
Method	Description
pd.concat([df1, df2])	Stack DataFrames on top of each other
pd.merge(df1, df2, on='id')	SQL-style join on a common key
df1.join(df2)	Join based on the index
